Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The ethical use of human participants in NLP research—particularly through crowdsourcing platforms—has gained attention, yet current frameworks remain reactive, static, and siloed within institutional review processes that were not designed for the scale, speed, and global distribution of digital labor. While Paper 1 rightly identifies gaps in applying the Belmont Report to modern NLP data practices, it stops short of offering a systematic, operational tool. Papers 2 and 3 introduce normative ethics and computational morality but do not bridge ethical theory with real-time risk assessment in data collection workflows. My idea builds on these foundations by proposing a *Dynamic Ethical Impact Assessment (DEIA) Framework* that operationalizes the three core principles of the Belmont Report—Respect for Persons, Beneficence, and Justice—not as one-time IRB checkboxes, but as continuously monitored, quantifiable metrics embedded directly into the NLP crowdsourcing pipeline. This framework introduces adaptability: it adjusts ethical safeguards based on task content, worker demographics, platform context, and psychological exposure risks (e.g., labeling traumatic text). Unlike prior work, DEIA integrates feedback loops from workers themselves, enabling participatory ethics design. It also leverages lightweight NLP monitoring to flag high-risk tasks (e.g., those involving violence or hate speech) and triggers enhanced consent protocols or compensation adjustments in real time. By transforming abstract ethical principles into measurable, actionable parameters, this approach shifts the field from post-hoc compliance to proactive ethical engineering—a critical evolution as AI systems increasingly depend on ethically sensitive human-generated data.

